						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">nicklausw wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm thinking lots of 8-bit registers that can be combined to form 16-bit registers. But to keep that from being literally the Z80, I guess they could also combine in certain combinations to form 24-bit, 32-bit...<br /><br />Honestly my ideal old console processor is a fast Z80. Not gonna lie. 65xx is more fun but Z80 makes way more sense to me.</div><br />There's the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zilog_eZ80" class="postlink">eZ80</a> which has 24-bit registers, a 3-stage pipeline, and which ditches the z80's 4-bit ALU for a 24-bit one, so it's pretty much a suped-up fast z80 in every way. Would be cool to see that in something that's not an embedded system with fixed code; the closest I've seen are some of TI's newer calculators.</div>

